Clustering (Part II)

Ryan Miller

Review - Clustering Terminology

  • The last presentation focused on \(k\)-means, a partitional clustering method that is prototype-based
    • Partitional meant it distinctly divided the data-points into non-overlapping subsets (clusters)
    • Prototype-based meant that each cluster is based upon a prototype (in \(k\)-means these are the centroids, or multi-dimensional means)
  • Today we will cover two topics:
    • How to accommodate categorical variables into clustering
    • Hierarchical clustering methods (which aren’t necessarily partitional and are not prototype-based)

Review - Distance

  • Recall that “good” clusters should contain data-points that are similar (close) to each other, and dissimilar (far) from data-points in other clusters

  • We’ve measured “closeness” using Euclidean distance: \[d_{a,b} = \sqrt{\sum_{j = 1}^{p} (x_{aj} - x_{bj})^2}\]

  • We could represent the closeness of the \(n\) data-points in a dataset using an \(n\)-by-\(n\) distance matrix, for example:

USA2 <- select(USArrests, "UrbanPop", "Murder")
distance <- get_dist(USA2)
fviz_dist(distance)

Gower Distance

  • Euclidean distance can only be calculated for numeric variables, but an alternative measure is Gower Distance

  • To calculate Gower distance, we consider a pair of data-points, indexed as “a” and “b”, then define: \[d_{a,b} = \sum_{j = 1}^{p} h_j( x_{a,j}, x_{b,j})\]

  • Where the function \(h_j()\) depends on the type of variable \(j\)
    • For numeric variables, \(h_j(x_{a,j}, x_{b,j}) = \tfrac{|x_{a,j} - x_{b,j}|}{R_j}\), where \(R_j\) is the range of the \(j^{th}\) variable
    • For categorical variables, \(h_j(x_{a,j}, x_{b,j}) = 0\) if the \(x_{a,j}\) and \(x_{b,j}\) are the same category, and \(h_j(x_{a,j}, x_{b,j}) = 1\) otherwise

Example - Clustering Animals

  • The daisy function with the argument metric = "gower" can be used to find the distance matrix using Gower distance
  • We can then visualize that matrix using fviz_dist:
D <- daisy(as.data.frame(animals), metric = "gower")
fviz_dist(D)

Example - Clustering Animals

  • Unfortunately Gower distance can’t be used for \(k\)-means clustering, as centroids remain uncalculable (though some hybrid approaches have been proposed)
  • However, we can perform \(k\)-medoids clustering (often referred to as PAM, or Partitioning Around Medoids)
    • In PAM the prototypes are themselves data-points
    • Otherwise PAM is very similar to \(k\)-means, it is a partitional prototype-based method

Example - Clustering Animals

  • PAM clusters can only be visualized via a scatterplot when all of the involved variables are numeric
  • When the data include categorical predictors, the best representation can provide is the medoids themselves along with a silhouette plot:
D <- daisy(as.data.frame(animals), metric = "gower")
pm <- pam(D, k = 4)

# Print the medoids then plot the silhouettes
pm$medoids
## [1] "lob" "lio" "wha" "sal"
fviz_silhouette(silhouette(pm), label = TRUE, print.summary = FALSE)

Hierarchical Clustering

  • We’ll now transition into a completely different approach to clustering
  • Rather than creating distinct partitions of the data-points, we’ll instead organize them into a nested tree-like structure known as a dendrogram:

  • We can view the dendrogram as a series of nested clusters, the first branch seperates \(\{\text{ant, lob, fro,} \ldots \text{spi}\}\) from \(\{\text{cat, man, cow,} \ldots, \text{eag}\}\)
    • Each of these clusters can than be sub-divided by moving down the tree
    • The height at which two sub-clusters are merged reflects the average distance between those clusters

Hierarchical Clustering

  • A strength of heirarchical clustering is that it displays nested relationships (ie: clusters, sub-clusters, sub-sub-clusters, etc.)
    • Nevertheless, we can always cut a dendrogram to obtain non-overlapping clusters
fviz_dend(ag, k = 4) + labs(title = "Clustering Animals (k = 4)")

Hierarchical Clustering - Algorithms

  • There are two broad approaches to hierarchical clustering (ie: creating a dendrogram)
    • Agglomerative, or “bottom-up” approaches, which start with each data-point as its own cluster (leaf), and then combine similar clusters (branches) until all of the data-points are grouped together in single cluster (root)
    • Divisive, or “top-down” approaches, which start all of the data-points in a single cluster (root); this cluster is then divided into smaller clusters (branches) based upon dissimilarity, divisions continue until each data-point is its own cluster.
  • The acronyms AGNES (AGglomerative NESting) and DIANA (DIvisive ANAlysis) describe two of the most popular of these approaches
D <- daisy(as.data.frame(animals), metric = "gower")

ag <- agnes(D)
fviz_dend(ag, k = 3) + labs(title = "Clustering Animals (AGNES)")

di <- diana(D)
fviz_dend(di, k = 3) + labs(title = "Clustering Animals (DIANA)")

Hierarchical Clustering - Closing Remarks

  • Because hierarchical clustering algorithms are greedy, divisive and agglomerative approaches rarely yield the same results
    • Agglomerative algorithms are much more computationally efficient (fewer splits to check), and consequently tend to be more widely used
  • We won’t fully explore the AGNES or DIANA algorithms, but you can find more details on them (as well as other clustering methods we don’t have time to cover) in this reference: https://www-users.cs.umn.edu/~kumar001/dmbook/ch8.pdf (start at page 516 for Hierarchical Clustering)
